{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}

<div class="accordion mb-3" id="unit01-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-01-a", "Summary: What is the adjective order in English?") %}
  <p>English adjectives before a noun follow this sequence:</p>
  <p>
    <span class="quantity fw-bold">Quantity</span> →
    <span class="opinion fw-bold">Opinion</span> →
    <span class="size fw-bold">Size</span> →
    <span class="age fw-bold">Age</span> →
    <span class="shape fw-bold">Shape</span> →
    <span class="color fw-bold">Colour</span> →
    <span class="origin fw-bold">Origin</span> →
    <span class="material fw-bold">Material</span> →
    <span class="purpose fw-bold">Purpose</span> → <strong>NOUN</strong>
  </p>
  <p>Memory aid: <strong>Q-OSASCOMP</strong></p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-01-b", "Why do native speakers find wrong order jarring?") %}
  <p>
    Native speakers acquire adjective order implicitly during language development — they
    never consciously learn the rule but internalise it as part of the grammar of English.
    When the order is violated, it creates a processing mismatch that feels unnatural,
    similar to hearing a sentence with the words in the wrong syntactic position.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-01-c", "What are the limitations of the tool?") %}
  <p>
    The tool classifies adjectives using a fixed dictionary. This means:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Adjectives not in the list default to the <span class="opinion">opinion</span> category</li>
    <li>Context-dependent adjectives (e.g. <em>light</em> — size or colour?) may be misclassified</li>
    <li>It works best with simple noun phrases containing common adjectives</li>
  </ul>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

